==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Imperative
<hw>Im*per"a*tive</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧m*p⟦ecr⟧r"⟦adot⟧*t⟦icr⟧v)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>imperativus</ets>, fr. <ets>imperare</ets>
to command; pref. <ets>im-</ets> in + <ets>parare</ets> to make ready,
prepare: cf. F. <ets>imp⟦eacute⟧ratif</ets>. See <er>Perade</er>, and
cf. <er>Empire</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Expressive of command;
containing positive command; authoritatively or absolutely directive;
commanding; authoritative; <as>as, <ex>imperative</ex>
orders</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The suit of kings are <qex>imperative</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Hall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not to be avoided or evaded; obligatory; binding;
compulsory; <as>as, an <ex>imperative</ex> duty or order</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>Expressive of command, entreaty,
advice, or exhortation; <as>as, the <ex>imperative</ex>
mood</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Imperative</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Imperative
<hw>Im*per"a*tive</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>The
imperative mood; also, a verb in the imperative mood.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Imperatively</ent>⟦br⟧
